{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539394"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16593"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16593"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.22,0.01,0.01,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9284"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100535"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9284"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82952"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1021"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3572"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48780"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100535"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent due to fatigue and dizziness. Over the past six months, she has lost 15 kg through restricted eating and excessive exercise, though her body mass index remains 24 kg/m2. She describes intense fear of weight gain and body image disturbance. She has withdrawn from social activities and become preoccupied with counting calories. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears tired. Her pulse rate is 48/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. She has cold peripheries and fine lanugo hair on her arms. Her heart sounds are normal with no murmur.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Outpatient dietitian referral only","Cognitive behavioural therapy only","Reassurance and review in one month","Exercise physiologist referral","Immediate hospital admission"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with atypical anorexia nervosa, characterised by all the features of anorexia nervosa (restricted eating, fear of weight gain, body image disturbance) but with a weight that remains within or above the normal range. Despite the \u0027normal\u0027 BMI, the significant recent weight loss and concerning vital signs indicate medical instability requiring urgent intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate hospital admission\u003C/strong\u003E is warranted due to the presence of medical compromise, specifically bradycardia (heart rate 48/min) and hypotension. The rate and amount of weight loss (15 kg in six months) is also concerning, regardless of current BMI. Medical stabilisation is the priority before addressing the psychological aspects of the eating disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that paediatric admission criteria for eating disorders differ from adult criteria with the following recommendations for admission criteria for children (from the Royal Children\u0027s Hospital): \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESignificant electrolyte disturbance (K \u0026lt; 3.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHR \u2264 50bpm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPostural HR increase \u226530 bpm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResting systolic BP \u226480 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPostural systolic drop \u2265 20mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypothermia \u0026lt;35.5C\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDehydration\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArrhythmia or prolonged QTc \u0026gt;0.45s\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWeight \u0026lt;75% of their expected body weight or rapid weight loss (\u0026gt;10-15% in 3-6 months is significant)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOut of control ED compensatory behaviours eg prolonged fasting/ inability to eat at home/ uncontrolled purging and exercising\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and review in one month\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous given the medical instability. The presence of bradycardia indicates significant medical risk that requires immediate attention, regardless of the patient\u0027s current weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOutpatient dietitian referral\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient given the medical complications present. While nutritional rehabilitation is important, it should be initiated in an inpatient setting when there are signs of medical compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECognitive behavioural therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is an important component of eating disorder treatment, but addressing medical stability takes precedence. Psychological interventions should be initiated once medical stability is achieved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExercise physiologist referral\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate at this stage as exercise should be restricted until medical stability is achieved. The patient\u0027s current excessive exercise is likely contributing to her medical compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights that serious medical complications can occur in eating disorders regardless of BMI, and that the rate and extent of weight loss are more important predictors of medical risk than absolute weight. Atypical anorexia nervosa carries similar medical risks to traditional anorexia nervosa and requires equally prompt intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atypical anorexia nervosa meets all diagnostic criteria for anorexia nervosa except significant weight loss, yet carries similar medical risks.","Rapid weight loss, even within a healthy BMI range, can cause serious medical complications including bradycardia and electrolyte disturbances.","Early intervention in eating disorders improves outcomes regardless of the patient\u0027s weight."],"references":["Hay P, Chinn D, Forbes D, Madden S, Newton R, Sugenor L, Touyz S, Ward W. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists clinical practice guidelines for the treatment of eating disorders. Australian \u0026 New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry. 2014 Nov;48(11):977-1008.","Rowe E. Early detection of eating disorders in general practice. Aust Fam Physician. 2017;46(11):833\u2013838. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/november/early-detection-of-eating-disorders","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Management of Eating Disorders in the Emergency Department. Melbourne: RCH; 2017. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Management_of_Eating_Disorders_in_the_Emergency_Department/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82952"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16593"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82952"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-26T10:41:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-26T10:42:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9284"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100535"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG